SIMPLE: troop
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Troop
<hw>Troop</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>troupe</ets>,
OF. <ets>trope</ets>, <ets>trupe</ets>, LL. <ets>troppus</ets>; of
uncertain origin; cf. Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧orp</ets> a hamlet, village, G.
<ets>dorf</ets> a village, dial. G. <ets>dorf</ets> a meeting. Norw.
<ets>torp</ets> a little farm, a crowd, E. <ets>thorp</ets>. Cf.
<er>Troupe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A collection of people; a
company; a number; a multitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which should accompany old age --⟦br⟧
As honor, love, obedience, <qex>troops</qex> of friends --⟦br⟧
I must not look to have.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Soldiers, collectively; an army; -- now generally
used in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Farewell the plumed <qex>troop</qex>, and the big wars.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>troops</qex> moved to victory with the precision of
machines.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>Specifically, a small body of
cavalry, light horse, or dragoons, consisting usually of about sixty
men, commanded by a captain; the unit of formation of cavalry,
corresponding to the <xex>company</xex> in infantry. Formerly, also, a
company of horse artillery; a battery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A company of stageplayers; a troupe.</def>
<rj><au>W. Coxe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A particular roll of the drum; a
quick march.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>See <er>Boy scout</er>, above.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Troop
<hw>Troop</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Trooped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trooping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move in numbers;
to come or gather in crowds or troops.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Armies . . .
<xex>troop</xex> to their standard.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To march on; to go forward in haste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor do I, as an enemy to peace,⟦br⟧
<qex>Troop</qex> in the throngs of military men.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Troop
<hw>Troop</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <cs>-- <mcol><col><b>To troop the
colors</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To troop the
colours</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>in the British army, to
perform a ceremony consisting essentially in carrying the colors,
accompanied by the band and escort, slowly before the troops drawn up in
single file and usually in a hollow square, as in London on the
sovereign's birthday.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troopbird</ent>⟦br⟧
